{"title_page": "Anastasia Ailamaki", "text_new": "{{short description|Greek/Swiss computer scientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Anastasia Ailamaki\n|image             = \n|birth_place       = Cyprus\n|nationality       = Greek\n|alma_mater        = [[University of Patras]]<br>[[Technical University of Crete]]<br>[[Rochester University]]<br>[[University of Wisconsin-Madison]]\n|image_caption     =  \n|field             = [[Computer science]]\n|work_institutions = [[Carnegie Mellon University]]<br>[[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne]]\n}}\n\n'''Anastasia Ailamaki''' is a [[Professor]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://actualites.epfl.ch/presseinfo-com?id=529|title=Anastasia Ailamaki appointed as a full professor of computer science|accessdate=22 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224112146/http://actualites.epfl.ch/presseinfo-com?id=529|archivedate=24 December 2013|publisher=\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne|df=dmy-all}}</ref> of Computer Sciences at the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne]] (EPFL) in [[Switzerland]] and the Director of the [https://www.epfl.ch/labs/dias/ Data-Intensive Applications and Systems] (DIAS) lab. She is also the co-founder of [https://www.raw-labs.com RAW Labs SA], a swiss company developing real-time analytics infrastructures for heterogeneous big data. Prior she was an associate professor of computer science at [[Carnegie Mellon School of Computer Science]].<ref name=\"cs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~natassa/|title=Anastasia Ailamaki|accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref> \n\nAnastasia's research interests are in the broad area of database systems and applications, with emphasis on database system behavior on modern processor hardware and disks. Her projects aim at building systems to strengthen the interaction between the database software and the underlying hardware and I/O devices. She is also working on automated schema design and computational database support for scientific applications, as well as storage device modeling, performance prediction, and internet query caching.\n\nAnastasia studied [[computer science]] at the [[University of Patras]], and earned her first [[master's degree]] at the [[Technical University of Crete]] followed by a second diploma from the [[University of Rochester]]. She received her Ph.D. in computer science from the [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.greekreporter.com/2014/06/13/professor-anastasia-ailamaki-thrives-abroad/|title=Professor Anastasia Ailamaki Thrives Abroad {{!}} Greek Reporter Europe|author=Matsaidoni, Theodora|accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe is the recipient of ten ''Best Paper'' and ''Best Demo'' awards and was awarded ''Young Investigator Award '' by the [[European Science Foundation]]. In 2013 she received an ''ERC Consolidator Award''  for the [https://www.epfl.ch/labs/dias/research/raw/ ViDa: Transforming raw data into information through virtualization] project.  She is an [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|IEEE]] and an [[Association for Computing Machinery|ACM]] Fellow and the Vice Chair of the Special Interest Group of Management of Data ([[SIGMOD]]) within the [[Association for Computing Machinery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.epfl.ch/anastasia.ailamaki|title=Anastasia Ailamaki|publisher=\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne|accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref> She is a member of the [[Expert network|Expert Network]] of the [[World Economic Forum]] and CRA-W mentor.\n\nAnastasia is the author of over 200 [[peer-review]]ed articles published in such journals as the ''[[Conference on Innovative Data Systems Research]]'', ''[[VLDB conference|VLDB]]'', [[SIGMOD]], ''[[ACM Transactions on Database Systems]]''.\n\n== Honors and Awards ==\n\n# '''[https://sigmod.org/sigmod-awards/people/anastasia-ailamaki-2019-sigmod-edgar-f-codd-innovations-award/ ACM SIGMOD Edgar F. Codd Innovations Award (2019)]:''' ''the SIGMOD Edgar F. Codd Innovations Award is given for innovative and highly significant contributions of enduring value to the development, understanding, or use of database systems.''\n# '''[http://www.nemitsasfoundation.org/en/nemitsas-prize-2018.html NEMITSAS Prize 2018 in Computer Science:]''' ''the President of the Republic of Cyprus, on behalf of the Takis and Louki Nemitsas Foundation, presents the Nemitsas Prize to one laureate for contributions in his/her scientific field which have been recognized at an international level.''\n# '''[https://actu.epfl.ch/news/anastasia-ailamaki-recognized-as-ieee-fellow-201-4/ IEEE Fellow (since 01/2018):]''' \u201cFor contributions to hardware-conscious database systems and scientific data management\u201d: ''IEEE Fellow is a distinction reserved for select IEEE members whose extraordinary accomplishments in any of the IEEE fields of interest are deemed fitting of this prestigious grade elevation.''\n# '''[https://www.acm.org/articles/people-of-acm/2016/anastasia-ailamaki ACM Fellow (since 01/2015):]''' \u201cFor contributions to the design, implementation, and evaluation of modern database systems\u201d: ''ACM's most prestigious member grade recognizes the top 1% of ACM members for their outstanding accomplishments in computing and information technology and/or outstanding service to ACM and the larger computing community.''\n# '''Elected Vice Chair, ACM SIGMOD Executive Committee (2013-2017)'''\n# '''ACM SIGMOD Doctoral Dissertation Award,''' for the thesis of Ryan Johnson, 2012: t''his award is the ACM SIGMOD\u2019s highest recognition of excellent research by doctoral candidates in the database field.''\n# '''European Young Investigator Award''' from the European Science Foundation, 2007: ''EurYI is a 1M Euro research grant which recognizes excellent track record and the applicant\u2019s potential to become world class leader in their chosen field of research.''\n# '''Finmeccanica fellowship''' from Computer Science Department at Carnegie Mellon, 2007: ''endowed in 1989, the Italian Finmeccanica Fellowship \"acknowledges promising young faculty members in the field of computer science\".''\n# '''Sloan Research Fellowship,''' February 2005: ''the Sloan Research Fellowship awards are intended to enhance the careers of the very best young faculty members in specified fields of science.''\n# '''NSF Faculty Early CAREER Award''' (CAREER), 2002: ''the CAREER program replaced the Presidential Young Investigator (PYI) program in 1995. Awardees are selected from among the most meritorious junior investigators funded by the National Science Foundation (NSF).''\n# '''IBM University Faculty Partnership Award,''' 2001-02, 2002-03, 2003-04: ''this highly competitive award recognizes the quality of faculty research programs and their importance to industry.''\n# Carnegie Mellon University '''Berkman Faculty Development Award''', 2001\n# University of Wisconsin - Madison '''Anthony C. Klug NCR Graduate Fellowship'''in Database Systems, 1998-2000.\n# Ranked 3<sup>rd</sup>in the 2nd Panhellenic Mathematics Olympiad. Athens, Greece, 1985.\n# Honor medal in the 3nd Panbalcanic Mathematics Olympiad. Sofia, Bulgaria, 1985.\n\n== PhD Theses ==\n\n# Georgios Psaropoulos. \u201cImproving Main-memory Database System Performance through Cooperative Multitasking\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 9712, October 2019.\n# Matthaios Alexandros Olma. \u201cTimely and cost-efficient data exploration through adaptive tuning\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 9636, October 2019.\n# Eleni Tzirita-Zacharatou. \u201cEfficient Query Processing for Spatial and Temporal Data Exploration\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 9637, August 2019.\n# Mirjana Pavlovic. \u201cTime- and Space-Efficient Spatial Analytics\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 9130, February 2019.\n# Manos Karpathiotakis. \u201cJust-in-time Analytics over Heterogeneous Data and Hardware\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 8077, November 2017. '''EPFL Dimitris N. Chorafas Foundation Award (winner, 2018).'''\n# Iraklis Psaroudakis. \u201cScaling Up Concurrent Analytical Workloads on Multi-Core Servers\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 7222, October 2016.\n# Renata Borovica-Gajic. \u201cToward timely, predictable and cost-effective data analytics\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 7140, September 2016.\n# Danica Porobic. \u201cHigh-Performance Transaction Processing on Non-Uniform Hardware Topologies\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 7023, April 2016.\n# Ioannis Alagiannis. \u201cAdaptive Query Processing on Raw Data Files\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 6644, May 2015.\n# Adrian Popescu. \u201cRuntime Prediction for Scale-Out Data Analytics\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 6629, May 2015.\n# Pinar T\u00f6z\u00fcn. \u201cTransactions Chasing Scalability and Instruction Locality on Multicores\u201d,''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 6411, October 2014. '''ACM SIGMOD Jim Gray Doctoral Dissertation Award (honorable mention, 2016).'''\n# Farhan Tauheed. \u201cScalable Exploration of Spatial Data in Large-Scale Scientific Simulations\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 6125, February 2014.\n# Radu Stoica. \u201cFlash-aware Database Transactions\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 6121, February 2014.\n# Manoussos-Gavriil Athanassoulis. \u201cSolid-State Storage and Work Sharing for Efficient Scaleup Data Analytics\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory'', EPFL Thesis no 6032, December 2013.\n# Ippokratis Pandis. \u201cScalable transaction processing through data-oriented execution\u201d ''Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Carnegie Mellon University'', May 2012.\n# Ryan Johnson. \u201cScalable Storage Managers for the Multi-Core Era\u201d ''Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Carnegie Mellon University'', December 2010. '''ACM SIGMOD Jim Gray Doctoral Dissertation Award (winner, 2012).'''\n# Debabrata Dash. \u201cAutomated Physical Design: A Combinatorial Optimization Approach\u201d Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-11-104'', ''School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' February 2011.\n# Nikos Hardavellas. \u201cChip-Multiprocessors for Server Workloads\u201d Ph.D. Thesis, ''School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' July 2009.\n# Minglong Shao. \u201cEfficient data organization and management on heterogeneous storage hierarchies\u201d Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-07-170, School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' December 2007.\n# Stratos Papadomanolakis. \u201cAutomated Database Design for Large-Scale Scientific Applications\u201d. Ph.D. Thesis, Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Carnegie Mellon University, May 2007 \n# Christopher Colohan. \u201cApplying Thread-Level Speculation to Database Transactions\u201d. Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-05-188, School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' November 2005.\n# Stavros Harizopoulos. \u201cStaged Database Systems\u201d. Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-05-194, School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' December 2005.\n# Shimin Chen. \u201cRedesigning Database Systems in Light of CPU Cache Prefetching\u201d. Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-05-192, School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' December 2005.\n# Mengzhi Wang. \u201cPerformance Modeling of Storage Devices Using Machine Learning\u201d. Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-05-185, School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' January 2006.\n\n== Selected Conference Keynotes and Distinguished Invited Talks ==\n\n# ''\"JIT Works: Embracing Homogeneity to Scalabe Data analytics\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the 7<sup>th</sup>ACM IKDD CoDS and 25<sup>th</sup>COMAD, Hyderabad, India, January 2020.\n# ''\u201cIntelligent Real-time Query Engines\u201d.'' \u00a0'''Keynote''' at IEEE DSC 2019, Hangzhou, China, June 2019.\n# ''\"Hardware-conscious Query Processing in GPU-accelerated Analytical Engines\u201d'''''. Keynote''' at the SAP HANA Database Campus - Open House 2019, Walldorf, Germany, May 2019.\n# ''\u201cInnovation in distributed data management \u2013 implications for health care\u201d.'' '''Invited talk''' at the Healthcare Data Institute, Paris, France, '''September 2018.'''\n# \u201c''RAW \u2013 Fast Analysis on All Kinds of Data\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the Brazilian Symposium on Databases (SBBD), Rio De Janeiro, Brazil, August 2018.\n# ''\"Caching in the memory hierarchy: 5 Minutes Ought to be Enough for Everybody\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the Joint Workshop of HardBD & Active\u201918, Paris, France, April 2018. \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \n# \u201c''The next 700 Transaction Processing Engines\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the Ph.D. Workshop of the 41<sup>st</sup>International Conference on Very Large Data Bases (VLDB), Munich, Germany, August 2017.\n# ''\"Fast, just-in-time queries on heterogeneous scientific data\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the International Conference on Computational Science (ICCS), Zurich, Switzerland, June 2017.\n# \u201c''The next 700 Transaction Processing Engines\u201d.'' '''Opening Keynote''' at the 2017 ACM International Conference on Management of Data (SIGMOD), Chicago, Illinois, USA, May 2017.\n# ''\u201cFast, just-in-time queries on heterogeneous scientific data\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the 12th IEEE International Conference on eScience, Baltimore, MD, October 2016.\n# \u201c''Databases and Hardware: The Beginning and Sequel of a Beautiful Friendship\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the 41<sup>st</sup>International Conference on Very Large Data Bases (VLDB), Kona, Hawaii, September 2015.\n# \u201c''Running with scissors: Fast queries on just-in-time databases''\u201d. '''Opening Keynote''' at the 30<sup>th</sup>IEEE International Conference on Data Engineering (ICDE), Chicago, Illinois, April 2014. Same-title talk invited as a special seminar at the MIT Big Data Initiative, October 2014.\n# ''\"Discovering the human brain through big data exploration\u201d.'' '''Invited Talk''' at the French Academy of Sciences, February 2014.\n# ''\"Scientific Data Management: Not your everyday transaction\u201d.'' '''Invited Seminar''' at the College de France, March 2012.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{GoogleScholar|YdrkeNwAAAAJ}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ailamaki, Anastasia}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century births]]\n[[Category:American computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Greek women computer scientists]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison alumni]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Association for Computing Machinery]]\n\n\n{{US-compu-bio-stub}}\n{{Compu-scientist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Greek/Swiss computer scientist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Anastasia Ailamaki\n|image             = \n|birth_place       = Cyprus\n|nationality       = Greek\n|alma_mater        = [[University of Patras]]<br>[[Technical University of Crete]]<br>[[Rochester University]]<br>[[University of Wisconsin-Madison]]\n|image_caption     =  \n|field             = [[Computer science]]\n|work_institutions = [[Carnegie Mellon University]]<br>[[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne]]\n}}\n\n'''Anastasia Ailamaki''' is a [[Professor]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://actualites.epfl.ch/presseinfo-com?id=529|title=Anastasia Ailamaki appointed as a full professor of computer science|accessdate=22 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224112146/http://actualites.epfl.ch/presseinfo-com?id=529|archivedate=24 December 2013|publisher=\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne|df=dmy-all}}</ref> of Computer Sciences at the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne]] (EPFL) in [[Switzerland]] and the Director of the [https://www.epfl.ch/labs/dias/ Data-Intensive Applications and Systems] (DIAS) lab. She is also the co-founder of [https://www.raw-labs.com RAW Labs SA], a swiss company developing real-time analytics infrastructures for heterogeneous big data. Prior she was an associate professor of computer science at [[Carnegie Mellon School of Computer Science]].<ref name=\"cs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~natassa/|title=Anastasia Ailamaki|accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref> \n\nAnastasia's research interests are in the broad area of database systems and applications, with emphasis on database system behavior on modern processor hardware and disks. Her projects aim at building systems to strengthen the interaction between the database software and the underlying hardware and I/O devices. She is also working on automated schema design and computational database support for scientific applications, as well as storage device modeling, performance prediction, and internet query caching.\n\nAnastasia studied [[computer science]] at the [[University of Patras]], and earned her first [[master's degree]] at the [[Technical University of Crete]] followed by a second diploma from the [[University of Rochester]]. She received her Ph.D. in computer science from the [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.greekreporter.com/2014/06/13/professor-anastasia-ailamaki-thrives-abroad/|title=Professor Anastasia Ailamaki Thrives Abroad {{!}} Greek Reporter Europe|author=Matsaidoni, Theodora|accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe is the recipient of ten ''Best Paper'' and ''Best Demo'' awards and was awarded ''Young Investigator Award '' by the [[European Science Foundation]]. In 2013 she received an ''ERC Consolidator Award''  for the [https://www.epfl.ch/labs/dias/research/raw/ ViDa: Transforming raw data into information through virtualization] project.  She is an [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|IEEE]] and an [[Association for Computing Machinery|ACM]] Fellow and the Vice Chair of the Special Interest Group of Management of Data ([[SIGMOD]]) within the [[Association for Computing Machinery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.epfl.ch/anastasia.ailamaki|title=Anastasia Ailamaki|publisher=\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne|accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref> She is a member of the [[Expert network|Expert Network]] of the [[World Economic Forum]] and CRA-W mentor.\n\nAnastasia is the author of over 200 [[peer-review]]ed articles published in such journals as the ''[[Conference on Innovative Data Systems Research]]'', ''[[VLDB conference|VLDB]]'', [[SIGMOD]], ''[[ACM Transactions on Database Systems]]''.\n\n== Honors and Awards ==\n'''[https://sigmod.org/sigmod-awards/people/anastasia-ailamaki-2019-sigmod-edgar-f-codd-innovations-award/ ACM SIGMOD Edgar F. Codd Innovations Award (2019)]:''' ''the SIGMOD Edgar F. Codd Innovations Award is given for innovative and highly significant contributions of enduring value to the development, understanding, or use of database systems.''\n\n'''NEMITSAS Prize 2018 in Computer Science:''' ''the President of the Republic of Cyprus, on behalf of the Takis and Louki Nemitsas Foundation, presents the Nemitsas Prize to one laureate for contributions in his/her scientific field which have been recognized at an international level.''\n\n'''IEEE Fellow (since 01/2018):''' \u201cFor contributions to hardware-conscious database systems and scientific data management\u201d: ''IEEE Fellow is a distinction reserved for select IEEE members whose extraordinary accomplishments in any of the IEEE fields of interest are deemed fitting of this prestigious grade elevation.''\n\n'''ACM Fellow (since 01/2015):''' \u201cFor contributions to the design, implementation, and evaluation of modern database systems\u201d: ''ACM's most prestigious member grade recognizes the top 1% of ACM members for their outstanding accomplishments in computing and information technology and/or outstanding service to ACM and the larger computing community.''\n\n'''Elected Vice Chair, ACM SIGMOD Executive Committee (2013-2017)'''\n\n'''ACM SIGMOD Doctoral Dissertation Award,''' for the thesis of Ryan Johnson, 2012: t''his award is the ACM SIGMOD\u2019s highest recognition of excellent research by doctoral candidates in the database field.''\n\n'''European Young Investigator Award''' from the European Science Foundation, 2007: ''EurYI is a 1M Euro research grant which recognizes excellent track record and the applicant\u2019s potential to become world class leader in their chosen field of research.''\n\n'''Finmeccanica fellowship'''from Computer Science Department at Carnegie Mellon, 2007: ''endowed in 1989, the Italian Finmeccanica Fellowship \"acknowledges promising young faculty members in the field of computer science\".''\n\n'''Sloan Research Fellowship,''' February 2005: ''the Sloan Research Fellowship awards are intended to enhance the careers of the very best young faculty members in specified fields of science.''\n\n'''NSF Faculty Early CAREER Award'''(CAREER), 2002: ''the CAREER program replaced the Presidential Young Investigator (PYI) program in 1995. Awardees are selected from among the most meritorious junior investigators funded by the National Science Foundation (NSF).''\n\n'''IBM University Faculty Partnership Award,'''2001-02, 2002-03, 2003-04: ''this highly competitive award recognizes the quality of faculty research programs and their importance to industry.''\n\nCarnegie Mellon University '''Berkman Faculty Development Award''', 2001\n\nUniversity of Wisconsin - Madison '''Anthony C. Klug NCR Graduate Fellowship'''in Database Systems, 1998-2000.\n\nRanked 3<sup>rd</sup>in the 2nd Panhellenic Mathematics Olympiad. Athens, Greece, 1985.\n\nHonor medal in the 3nd Panbalcanic Mathematics Olympiad. Sofia, Bulgaria, 1985.\n\n== PhD Theses ==\n[1] \u00a0Georgios Psaropoulos. \u201cImproving Main-memory Database System Performance through Cooperative Multitasking\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 9712, October 2019.\n\n[2] \u00a0Matthaios Alexandros Olma. \u201cTimely and cost-efficient data exploration through adaptive tuning\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 9636, October 2019.\n\n[3] \u00a0Eleni Tzirita-Zacharatou. \u201cEfficient Query Processing for Spatial and Temporal Data Exploration\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 9637, August 2019.\n\n[4] \u00a0Mirjana Pavlovic. \u201cTime- and Space-Efficient Spatial Analytics\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 9130, February 2019.\n\n[5] \u00a0Manos Karpathiotakis. \u201cJust-in-time Analytics over Heterogeneous Data and Hardware\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 8077, November 2017. '''EPFL Dimitris N. Chorafas Foundation Award (winner, 2018).'''\n\n[6] \u00a0Iraklis Psaroudakis. \u201cScaling Up Concurrent Analytical Workloads on Multi-Core Servers\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 7222, October 2016.\n\n[7] \u00a0Renata Borovica-Gajic. \u201cToward timely, predictable and cost-effective data analytics\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,'' EPFL Thesis no 7140, September 2016.\n\n[8] \u00a0Danica Porobic. \u201cHigh-Performance Transaction Processing on Non-Uniform Hardware Topologies\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 7023, April 2016.\n\n[9] \u00a0Ioannis Alagiannis. \u201cAdaptive Query Processing on Raw Data Files\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 6644, May 2015.\n\n[10] \u00a0Adrian Popescu. \u201cRuntime Prediction for Scale-Out Data Analytics\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 6629, May 2015.\n\n[11] \u00a0Pinar T\u00f6z\u00fcn. \u201cTransactions Chasing Scalability and Instruction Locality on Multicores\u201d,''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 6411, October 2014. '''ACM SIGMOD Jim Gray Doctoral Dissertation Award (honorable mention, 2016).'''\n\n[12] \u00a0Farhan Tauheed. \u201cScalable Exploration of Spatial Data in Large-Scale Scientific Simulations\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 6125, February 2014.\n\n[13] \u00a0Radu Stoica. \u201cFlash-aware Database Transactions\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory,''EPFL Thesis no 6121, February 2014.\n\n[14] \u00a0Manoussos-Gavriil Athanassoulis. \u201cSolid-State Storage and Work Sharing for Efficient Scaleup Data Analytics\u201d, ''School of Computer and Communication Sciences, DIAS Laboratory'', EPFL Thesis no 6032, December 2013.\n\n[15] \u00a0Ippokratis Pandis. \u201cScalable transaction processing through data-oriented execution\u201d ''Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Carnegie Mellon University'', May 2012.\n\n[16] \u00a0Ryan Johnson. \u201cScalable Storage Managers for the Multi-Core Era\u201d ''Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Carnegie Mellon University'', December 2010. '''ACM SIGMOD Jim Gray Doctoral Dissertation Award (winner, 2012).'''\n\n[17] \u00a0Debabrata Dash. \u201cAutomated Physical Design: A Combinatorial Optimization Approach\u201d Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-11-104'', ''School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' February 2011.\n\n[18] \u00a0Nikos Hardavellas. \u201cChip-Multiprocessors for Server Workloads\u201d Ph.D. Thesis, ''School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' July 2009.\n\n[19] \u00a0Minglong Shao. \u201cEfficient data organization and management on heterogeneous storage hierarchies\u201d Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-07-170, School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' December 2007.\n\n[20] \u00a0Stratos Papadomanolakis. \u201cAutomated Database Design for Large-Scale Scientific Applications\u201d. Ph.D. Thesis, Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Carnegie Mellon University, May 2007 \n\n[21] \u00a0Christopher Colohan. \u201cApplying Thread-Level Speculation to Database Transactions\u201d. Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-05-188, School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' November 2005.\n\n[22] \u00a0Stavros Harizopoulos. \u201cStaged Database Systems\u201d. Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-05-194, School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' December 2005.\n\n[23] \u00a0Shimin Chen. \u201cRedesigning Database Systems in Light of CPU Cache Prefetching\u201d. Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-05-192, School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' December 2005.\n\n[24] \u00a0Mengzhi Wang. \u201cPerformance Modeling of Storage Devices Using Machine Learning\u201d. Ph.D. dissertation available as ''Technical Report CMU-CS-05-185, School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,'' January 2006.\n\n== Selected Conference Keynotes and Distinguished Invited Talks ==\n''\"JIT Works: Embracing Homogeneity to Scalabe Data analytics\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the 7<sup>th</sup>ACM IKDD CoDS and 25<sup>th</sup>COMAD, Hyderabad, India, January 2020.\n\n''\u201cIntelligent Real-time Query Engines\u201d.'' \u00a0'''Keynote''' at IEEE DSC 2019, Hangzhou, China, June 2019.\n\n''\"Hardware-conscious Query Processing in GPU-accelerated Analytical Engines\u201d'''''. Keynote''' at the SAP HANA Database Campus - Open House 2019, Walldorf, Germany, May 2019.\n\n''\u201cInnovation in distributed data management \u2013 implications for health care\u201d.'' '''Invited talk''' at the Healthcare Data Institute, Paris, France, '''September 2018.'''\n\n\u201c''RAW \u2013 Fast Analysis on All Kinds of Data\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the Brazilian Symposium on Databases (SBBD), Rio De Janeiro, Brazil, August 2018.\n\n''\"Caching in the memory hierarchy: 5 Minutes Ought to be Enough for Everybody\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the Joint Workshop of HardBD & Active\u201918, Paris, France, April 2018. \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \n\n\u201c''The next 700 Transaction Processing Engines\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the Ph.D. Workshop of the 41<sup>st</sup>International Conference on Very Large Data Bases (VLDB), Munich, Germany, August 2017.\n\n''\"Fast, just-in-time queries on heterogeneous scientific data\u201d.'' '''Keynote''' at the International Conference on Computational Science (ICCS), Zurich, Switzerland, June 2017.\n\n\u201c''The next 700 Transaction Processing Engines\u201d.'' '''Opening Keynote''' at the 2017 ACM International Conference on Management of Data (SIGMOD), Chicago, Illinois, USA, May 2017.\n\n''\u201cFast, just-in-time queries on heterogeneous scienti