{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bhutan", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Bhutan}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bhutan\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Bhutan]]\n| first_case = [[Paro, Bhutan|Paro]]\n| arrival_date = 6 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=6|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| recovery_cases = 2\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 5\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Bhutan]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n===March 2020===\n'''6 March:''' Bhutan confirmed its first COVID-19 case, a 76-year-old US male who travelled to the country via India. Around 90 people who came directly in contact with him, along with his 59-year-old partner, driver, and guide were quarantined.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/bhutan-confirms-first-coronavirus-case/articleshow/74506428.cms|title=Bhutan confirms first coronavirus case|date=6 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBhutan immediately restricted entry of foreign tourists for two weeks. Schools in three areas including capital [[Thimphu]] were closed.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe 76-year-old American male was evacuated to the United States on 13 March.\n\n'''20 March:''' the 59-year old partner of the American tourist tested positive for COVID-19<ref>{{cite news |last=Wangchuk |first=Kinga |date=22 March 2020 |title=Bhutan Confrms Second COVID-19 Case |url= |work=[[The Journalist (Bhutan)|The Journalist]] |location= Thimphu|access-date= }}</ref> 14 days into quarantine, 19 days after entering Bhutan and 28 days after her first contact with the index case.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thebhutanese.bt/partner-tests-positive-14-days-into-quarantine-19-days-into-entering-bhutan-and-28-days-after-1st-contact-with-index-case/ |title=Partner tests positive 14 days into quarantine, 19 days into entering Bhutan and 28 days after 1st contact with index case. |author=Tenzing Lamsang  |date=21 March 2020 |website=The Bhutanese |publisher= |access-date=31 March 2020 }}</ref> Although their driver and guide tested negative, both were being held in extended quarantine even though their quarantine period had ended.<ref>{{cite news\n| author       =<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n| title        = Bhutan detects 2nd confirmed COVID-19 case\n| url          = http://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=129933\n| publisher    = Bhutan Broadcasting Service \n| publication-date = 20 March 2020\n| work         = BBS\n| location     = Thimphu\n| date         = 20 March 2020\n| access-date  =20 March 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n'''22 March:''' [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]], the king of Bhutan, announced in a national address that the country's land borders would be sealed off.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/tv/B-D3w59BjPB/|title=Instagram post by Her Majesty Queen Jetsun Pema \u2022 Mar 23, 2020 at 3:10am UTC|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n'''23 March:''' All International borders were sealed. Around 5,000 Bhutanese living the Indian town of [[Jaigaon]] West Bengal, bordering Bhutan were evacuated to neighbouring [[Phuntsholing]].<ref name-\"BBS_130765\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130765|title=Bhutanese evacuees from Jaigaon well looked after by the Office of the Gyalpoi Zimpon |author=Sonam Penjor  |date=7 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=8 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n'''24 March:''' The government banned the import of Doma ([[betel nut]]) and Pani ([[betel leaf]]), as well as fruit, vegetables, and meat in an effort to curb the spread of coronavirus.<ref name=\"nenow.in\">{{Cite web|url=https://nenow.in/health/bhutan-confirms-third-covid-19-case.html|title=Bhutan confirms third COVID-19 case|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> It also closed all its borders with India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nenow.in/neighbour/bhutan/bhutan-government-closes-all-international-borders-with-india.html|title=Coronavirus: Bhutan government closes all international borders with India|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''25 March:''' A student in Bhutan who had returned from the United Kingdom was found to be positive for COVID-19, the third case in the country.<ref>{{cite news |author=Youten Tshedup |date=27 March 2020 |title= First Bhutanese to test positive for Covid-19 |url=https://kuenselonline.com/first-bhutanese-to-test-positive-for-covid-19/ |work=[[Kuensel]] |location= Thimphu|access-date=27 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"nenow.in\"/>\n\n'''29 March:'''  According to the [[Ministry of Health (Bhutan)|Ministry of Health]], a returning student in the quarantine facility tested positive. The patient was moved to the isolation ward in Thimphu.<ref>{{cite tweet |user= MoHBhutan  |number=1244101376004837376 |date=29 March 2020 |title=Update: 4th case.|quote= 1 student from the facility quarantine tested Positive and is now shifted to the Isolation ward, Thimphu. instagram.com/p/B-TVqm-A9fy/ |access-date=29 March 2020 }}</ref> This is the 4th positive case in Bhutan and the 2nd Bhutanese to be infected by COVID-19 in the country. A Bhutanese national in [[New York City|New York]] was also confirmed positive.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=PMBhutan |number=1244187470876434433 |date=29 March 2020 |title=Message from the Prime Minister |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''31 March:''' the Prime Minister, [[Lotay Tshering|Dr. Lotay Tshering]], announced that the quarantine period for COVID-19 in Bhutan  will be extended from 14 to 21 days, even though the international (WHO) standard for quarantine is 14 days. He said: \u201c''There is the risk of testing positive even after quarantining for 14 days. That is why we have decided to extend the quarantine period.''\u201d On this date Bhutan had 3,059 people held in quarantine facilities and 339 people in home quarantine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://south-asian-monitor.com/en/bhutan/bhutan-extends-quarantine-period-for-covid-19-to-21-days |title=Bhutan extends quarantine period for COVID-19 to 21 days  |author= <!--Not stated--> |date=31 March 2020 |website=South Asian Monitor  |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n'''1 April:''' it was announced that a Butanese student who had been studying in the US, and was under facility quarantine in Thimphu, has tested positive for Coronavirus.  She has been moved to the isolation centre and is reported to be in a stable condition. This is the 5th case of COVID-19 detected in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130544 |title=COVID-19 Status in Bhutan & New York |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=3 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n'''2 April:''' It was announced that the first two COVID-19 cases detected in Bhutan (an American tourist and his travelling partner) have now recovered.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130632|title=Bhutan\u2019s first two COVID-19 patients have recovered |author=Passang Dorji  |date=3 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=3 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n'''7 April:''' With the numbers of coronavirus infections in neighbouring India rising, Increased security and prevention measures have been set up in the [[Sarpang District|Sarpang]] and [[Samtse District|Samtse]] districts which border the Indian states of Assam and West Bengal. These measures include round-the-clock surveillance of all formal and informal border crossing points, and door-to-door COVID-19 awareness and prevention campaigns.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130751 |title=COVID-19 control measures in Sarpang Dzongkhag |author=Karma Wangdi  |date=7 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=8 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130749 |title=Samtse Dzongkhag steps up COVID-19 preventive measures |author=<!--Not stated-->  |date=7 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=8 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Regional Referral Hospital Mongar Bhutan.jpg|thumb|Regional Referral Hospital, Mongar]]\n\n'''8 April:''' A special isolation hospital equipped to treat any COVID-19 patients in the eastern region has been set up in the Royal Guest House at [[Mongar]]. It has 24 beds with a surge capacity for an additional 15 beds. A COVID-19 testing lab was also set up at the Mongar Regional Referral Hospital and so till this date seven suspected cases had been tested there. All these test results were negative. The [[Mongar District]] administration has also identified 30 quarantine centres in the district. Currently only one person in the district is in quarantine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130813|title=COVID-19 Hospital in Monggar ready to handle any outbreak in the eastern region |author=Sonam Tshering  |date=8 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=8 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n'''9 April:''' 309 Bhutanese were evacuated from the [[Maldives]] and New Delhi in India and returned to Bhutan by special [[Drukair]]  flights. On arrival they were all sent directly to the quarantine facility in Thimphu. Most of those returning from the Maldves had been working in the tourism sector there; while the majority of those returning from New Delhi were students. The government scheduled further flights within the following days to evacuate Bhutanese residing in Bangalore, Amritsar and Chandigarh In india, and those residing in Sri Lanka. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://kuenselonline.com/309-return-from-india-and-the-maldives/|title=309 return from India and the Maldives   |author=Phub Dem  |date=10 April 2020 |website=Kuensel Online |publisher=[[Kuensel]] |access-date=10 April 2020 }}</ref>\n   \n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Summary of COVID-19 Medical Cases in Bhutan==\n{{2019\u201320_coronavirus_outbreak_data/Bhutan_medical_cases}}\n\n==Impact==\n\n===Agriculture===\n\n===Education===\n\n===Tourism===\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{Cite |author=Ministry of Health |author-link=Ministry of Health (Bhutan) |date=25 February 2020 |title=National Preparedness and Response Plan for Outbreak of Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cabinet.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/National-Preparedness-and-Response-Plan-3rd-ed-1-1.pdf |location=Thimphu |publisher=Ministry of Health, Royal Government of Bhutan |edition=3}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n\n* [http://www.moh.gov.bt/category/covid-19/ Ministry of Health, COVID-19]\n* [https://www.bbs.bt/news/?cat=9375  Bhutan Broadcastng Service, COVID-19 news]\n* [https://kuenselonline.com/covid-19/ Kuensel online. COVID-19 news]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bhutan| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in Bhutan]] \n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Bhutan]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Bhutan]] \n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Bhutan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Bhutan}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bhutan\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Bhutan]]\n| first_case = [[Paro, Bhutan|Paro]]\n| arrival_date = 6 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=6|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| recovery_cases = 2\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 5\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Bhutan]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n===March 2020===\n'''6 March:''' Bhutan confirmed its first COVID-19 case, a 76-year-old US male who travelled to the country via India. Around 90 people who came directly in contact with him, along with his 59-year-old partner, driver, and guide were quarantined.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/bhutan-confirms-first-coronavirus-case/articleshow/74506428.cms|title=Bhutan confirms first coronavirus case|date=6 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBhutan immediately restricted entry of foreign tourists for two weeks. Schools in three areas including capital [[Thimphu]] were closed.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe 76-year-old American male was evacuated to the United States on 13 March.\n\n'''20 March:''' the 59-year old partner of the American tourist tested positive for COVID-19<ref>{{cite news |last=Wangchuk |first=Kinga |date=22 March 2020 |title=Bhutan Confrms Second COVID-19 Case |url= |work=[[The Journalist (Bhutan)|The Journalist]] |location= Thimphu|access-date= }}</ref> 14 days into quarantine, 19 days after entering Bhutan and 28 days after her first contact with the index case.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thebhutanese.bt/partner-tests-positive-14-days-into-quarantine-19-days-into-entering-bhutan-and-28-days-after-1st-contact-with-index-case/ |title=Partner tests positive 14 days into quarantine, 19 days into entering Bhutan and 28 days after 1st contact with index case. |author=Tenzing Lamsang  |date=21 March 2020 |website=The Bhutanese |publisher= |access-date=31 March 2020 }}</ref> Although their driver and guide tested negative, both were being held in extended quarantine even though their quarantine period had ended.<ref>{{cite news\n| author       =<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->\n| title        = Bhutan detects 2nd confirmed COVID-19 case\n| url          = http://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=129933\n| publisher    = Bhutan Broadcasting Service \n| publication-date = 20 March 2020\n| work         = BBS\n| location     = Thimphu\n| date         = 20 March 2020\n| access-date  =20 March 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n'''22 March:''' [[Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck]], the king of Bhutan, announced in a national address that the country's land borders would be sealed off.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/tv/B-D3w59BjPB/|title=Instagram post by Her Majesty Queen Jetsun Pema \u2022 Mar 23, 2020 at 3:10am UTC|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n'''23 March:''' All International borders were sealed. Around 5,000 Bhutanese living the Indian town of [[Jaigaon]] West Bengal, bordering Bhutan were evacuated to neighbouring [[Phuntsholing]].<ref name-\"BBS_130765\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130765|title=Bhutanese evacuees from Jaigaon well looked after by the Office of the Gyalpoi Zimpon |author=Sonam Penjor  |date=7 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=8 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n'''24 March:''' The government banned the import of Doma ([[betel nut]]) and Pani ([[betel leaf]]), as well as fruit, vegetables, and meat in an effort to curb the spread of coronavirus.<ref name=\"nenow.in\">{{Cite web|url=https://nenow.in/health/bhutan-confirms-third-covid-19-case.html|title=Bhutan confirms third COVID-19 case|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> It also closed all its borders with India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nenow.in/neighbour/bhutan/bhutan-government-closes-all-international-borders-with-india.html|title=Coronavirus: Bhutan government closes all international borders with India|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''25 March:''' A student in Bhutan who had returned from the United Kingdom was found to be positive for COVID-19, the third case in the country.<ref>{{cite news |author=Youten Tshedup |date=27 March 2020 |title= First Bhutanese to test positive for Covid-19 |url=https://kuenselonline.com/first-bhutanese-to-test-positive-for-covid-19/ |work=[[Kuensel]] |location= Thimphu|access-date=27 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"nenow.in\"/>\n\n'''29 March:'''  According to the [[Ministry of Health (Bhutan)|Ministry of Health]], a returning student in the quarantine facility tested positive. The patient was moved to the isolation ward in Thimphu.<ref>{{cite tweet |user= MoHBhutan  |number=1244101376004837376 |date=29 March 2020 |title=Update: 4th case.|quote= 1 student from the facility quarantine tested Positive and is now shifted to the Isolation ward, Thimphu. instagram.com/p/B-TVqm-A9fy/ |access-date=29 March 2020 }}</ref> This is the 4th positive case in Bhutan and the 2nd Bhutanese to be infected by COVID-19 in the country. A Bhutanese national in [[New York City|New York]] was also confirmed positive.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=PMBhutan |number=1244187470876434433 |date=29 March 2020 |title=Message from the Prime Minister |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''31 March:''' the Prime Minister, [[Lotay Tshering|Dr. Lotay Tshering]], announced that the quarantine period for COVID-19 in Bhutan  will be extended from 14 to 21 days, even though the international (WHO) standard for quarantine is 14 days. He said: \u201c''There is the risk of testing positive even after quarantining for 14 days. That is why we have decided to extend the quarantine period.''\u201d On this date Bhutan had 3,059 people held in quarantine facilities and 339 people in home quarantine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://south-asian-monitor.com/en/bhutan/bhutan-extends-quarantine-period-for-covid-19-to-21-days |title=Bhutan extends quarantine period for COVID-19 to 21 days  |author= <!--Not stated--> |date=31 March 2020 |website=South Asian Monitor  |access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n'''1 April:''' it was announced that a Butanese student who had been studying in the US, and was under facility quarantine in Thimphu, has tested positive for Coronavirus.  She has been moved to the isolation centre and is reported to be in a stable condition. This is the 5th case of COVID-19 detected in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130544 |title=COVID-19 Status in Bhutan & New York |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=3 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n'''2 April:''' It was announced that the first two COVID-19 cases detected in Bhutan (an American tourist and his travelling partner) have now recovered.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130632|title=Bhutan\u2019s first two COVID-19 patients have recovered |author=Passang Dorji  |date=3 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=3 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n'''7 April:''' With the numbers of coronavirus infections in neighbouring India rising, Increased security and prevention measures have been set up in the [[Sarpang District|Sarpang]] and [[Samtse District|Samtse]] districts which border the Indian states of Assam and West Bengal. These measures include round-the-clock surveillance of all formal and informal border crossing points, and door-to-door COVID-19 awareness and prevention campaigns.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130751 |title=COVID-19 control measures in Sarpang Dzongkhag |author=Karma Wangdi  |date=7 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=8 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130749 |title=Samtse Dzongkhag steps up COVID-19 preventive measures |author=<!--Not stated-->  |date=7 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=8 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Regional Referral Hospital Mongar Bhutan.jpg|thumb|Regional Referral Hospital, Mongar]]\n\n'''8 April:''' A special isolation hospital equipped to treat any COVID-19 patients in the eastern region has been set up in the Royal Guest House at [[Mongar]]. It has 24 beds with a surge capacity for an additional 15 beds. A COVID-19 testing lab was also set up at the Mongar Regional Referral Hospital and so till this date seven suspected cases had been tested there. All these test results were negative. The [[Mongar District]] administration has also identified 30 quarantine centres in the district. Currently only one person in the district is in quarantine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbs.bt/news/?p=130813|title=COVID-19 Hospital in Monggar ready to handle any outbreak in the eastern region |author=Sonam Tshering  |date=8 April 2020 |website=BBS |publisher=Bhutan Broadcasting Service |access-date=8 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n'''9 April:''' 309 Bhutanese were evacuated from the [[Maldives]] and New Delhi in India and returned to Bhutan by special [[Drukair]]  flights. On arrival they were all sent directly to the quarantine facility in Thimphu. Most of those returning from the Maldves had been working in the tourism sector there; while the majority of those returning from New Delhi were students. The government scheduled further flights within the following days to evacuate Bhutanese residing in Bangalore, Amritsar and Chandigarh In india, and those residing in Sri Lanka. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://kuenselonline.com/309-return-from-india-and-the-maldives/|title=309 return from India and the Maldives   |author=Phub Dem  |date=10 April 2020 |website=Kuensel Online |publisher=[[Kuensel]] |access-date=10 April 2020 }}</ref>\n   \n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Summary of COVID-19 Medical Cases in Bhutan==\n{{2019\u201320_coronavirus_outbreak_data/Bhutan_medical_cases}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{Cite |author=Ministry of Health |author-link=Ministry of Health (Bhutan) |date=25 February 2020 |title=National Preparedness and Response Plan for Outbreak of Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cabinet.gov.bt/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/National-Preparedness-and-Response-Plan-3rd-ed-1-1.pdf |location=Thimphu |publisher=Ministry of Health, Royal Government of Bhutan |edition=3}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n\n* [http://www.moh.gov.bt/category/covid-19/ Ministry of Health, COVID-19]\n* [https://www.bbs.bt/news/?cat=9375  Bhutan Broadcastng Service, COVID-19 news]\n* [https://kuenselonline.com/covid-19/ Kuensel online. COVID-19 news]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bhutan| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in Bhutan]] \n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Bhutan]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Bhutan]] \n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Bhutan]]\n", "name_user": "CFynn", "label": "safe", "comment": "added section: Impact", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Bhutan"}
{"title_page": "KZ Tandingan", "text_new": "{{short description|Filipino singer and rapper}}\n{{About|the singer|her self-titled album|KZ Tandingan (album)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Philippine name|Lobrigas|Tandingan}}{{Infobox musical artist <!--Wikipedia:Musician -->\n| name             = KZ Tandingan\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = KZ Tandingan - 2019 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Tandingan in 2019\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Kristine Zhenie Lobrigas Tandingan\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1992|03|11}}\n| birth_place      = [[Digos]], Philippines\n| origin           = Manila, Philippines\n| genre            = [[Acoustic music|Acoustic jazz]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| occupation       = Singer, rapper\n| instrument       = Vocals, piano\n| years_active     = 2012\u2013present\n| nationality      = [[Filipino people|Filipino]]\n| label            = [[Star Music]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Charice Pempengco]], [[List of The X Factor Philippines (season 1) finalists|''Factor'' finalists]], [[Side A (band)|Side A]], TJ Monterde, DIVAS, ASAP Soul Sessions\n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| alias            = Asia's Soul Supreme\n}}\n\n'''Kristine Zhenie Lobrigas Tandingan'''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ph.omg.yahoo.com/news/kz-wins--the-x-factor-philippines-.html | title=KZ wins 'The X Factor Philippines' | publisher=[[omg!|Yahoo! OMG! Philippines]]| date=October 8, 2012 | accessdate=June 28, 2013 | author=Karen Valeza}}</ref> (born March 11, 1992), mononymously known as '''KZ''', is a Filipino singer and rapper. She rose to prominence following her win on the [[The X Factor Philippines (season 1)|first season]] of ''[[The X Factor Philippines]]'' in 2012.<ref name=\"Champion X Factor\">{{cite web | url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/10/07/12/kz-tandingan-wins-x-factor-ph | title=KZ Tandingan wins 'X Factor PH' | publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] | date=October 7, 2012 | accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThat same year, she won [[Aliw Award|Aliw Award for Best New Artist]]. She has released notable songs in the Philippines such as \"Darating Din\", \"Mahal Ko o Mahal Ako\" and \"[[Two Less Lonely People in the World]]\", which peaked at number 2 on the [[Philippine Hot 100]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://billboard.ph/billboardph-hot-100-august-21/|title=billboard.ph - Diese Website steht zum Verkauf! - Informationen zum Thema .|website=billboard.ph|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref>\n\nTandingan is one of the members of the Filipino girl group DIVAS along with [[Yeng Constantino]], [[Kyla]], and [[Angeline Quinto]].\n\nShe became known internationally when she joined ''[[Singer 2018]]'', a popular singing competition aired on [[Hunan Broadcasting System|HBS]].\n\n==Life and career==\n===Early life===\nKZ Tandingan started singing as a child but had to stop when she was in her junior year in high school after suffering from a throat problem. She is an alumna of [[University of Southeastern Philippines]] in Davao City and had graduated with a degree of Bachelor of Science in Biology.<ref name=\"Philstar Bio\">{{cite news | url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2013/07/05/961692/will-kz-tandingan-make-it-stardom | title=Will KZ Tandingan make it to stardom? | newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]] | date=July 5, 2013 | accessdate=July 11, 2013 | author=Baby A. Gil}}</ref>\n\nBefore she joined ''The X Factor Philippines'', Tandingan was part of a local acoustic band.<ref name=\"Philstar Bio\"/>\n\n===2012: ''The X Factor Philippines''===\nTandingan was considered as an early favorite after she performed a jazzy version of \"[[Somewhere Over the Rainbow]]\" in the fourth week of the Judges' auditions. After receiving a standing ovation from all the judges', she was requested to sing again. Tandingan obliged and sang \"[[Ready or Not (Fugees song)|Ready or Not]]\" by American hip-hop group, [[The Fugees]]. With her second song, she also showed her rapping skills. Tandingan was greatly praised by all of the judges. Nievera even shouted that, \"A star is born in Digos!\".<ref name=\"ABS1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/07/16/12/star-born-digos-x-factor-week-3 | title='A star is born' in Digos on 'X Factor ' week 3 | publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Public Affairs|ABS-CBN News]] | date=July 16, 2012 | accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref> The video of Tandingan's audition went viral online after it was uploaded in YouTube. The video reached nearly 1 million views before it was removed due to copyright issues.<ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mindanaotimes.net/kz-enters-x-factor-top-20/ | title=KZ enters \u2018X Factor\u2019 Top 20 | publisher=[[Mindanao Times]] | date=July 24, 2012 | accessdate=July 31, 2012 | author=Fabian, Chris}}</ref> During the Bootcamp stage, she sang \"Mahirap Magmahal ng Syota ng Iba\" by the [[APO Hiking Society]] and cried after she made the cut for the Top 20.<ref name=\"ABS2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/07/23/12/kz-tandingan-x-factor-top-20-osang-out | title=KZ Tandingan in 'X Factor' Top 20; Osang out | publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Public Affairs|ABS-CBN News]] | date=July 23, 2012 | accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref> Tandingan sang \"[[Killing Me Softly with His Song]]\" by [[Roberta Flack]] during the Judges' home visit. On week 9, she landed on the bottom 2 for the first time with teammate Allen Sta. Maria, but she survived elimination. Tandingan was Charice's last remaining act after Allen Sta. Maria was eliminated on week 9. She reached the grand finals on October 7, 2012 and was proclaimed the winner of ''The X Factor Philippines''.<ref name=\"Champion X Factor\"/>\n\n;Performances and results\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible autocollapse\" style=\" margin:1em auto 1em auto; text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#BFBFBF;\"| ''The X Factor Philippines'' season 1 performances and results\n|-\n! Stage\n! Theme\n! Song choice\n! Original artist\n! Order \n! Result\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Audition\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Free choice\n| \"[[Over the Rainbow]]\"\n| [[Judy Garland]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Advanced\n|-\n| \"[[Ready or Not (Fugees song)|Ready or Not]]\"\n| [[Fugees]]\n|-\n! Bootcamp 1\n| Specific song\n| \"[[Without You (David Guetta song)|Without You]]\"\n| [[David Guetta]]\n| {{N/A}}\n| Advanced\n|-\n! Bootcamp 2\n| Free choice\n| \"[[APO Hiking Society#Songs|Mahirap Magmahal Ng Syota Ng Iba]]\"\n| {{nowrap|[[APO Hiking Society]]}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| Advanced\n|-\n! {{nowrap|Judges' houses}}\n| Free choice\n| \"[[Killing Me Softly with His Song]]\"\n| [[Roberta Flack]]\n| {{N/A}}\n| Advanced\n|-\n! Top 12\n| [[Soundtrack|Songs from the movies]]\n| \"[[The Show (Lenka song)|The Show]]\"\n| [[Lenka]]\n| 6\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 11\n| {{nowrap|song with [[Life]] or [[Life|Buhay]] in the title}}\n| \"[[For Once in My Life]]\"\n| [[Stevie Wonder]]\n| 9\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 10\n| [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| \"[[In the End]]\"\n| [[Linkin Park]]\n| 10\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 9\n| Tribute to late music icons\n| \"[[Rehab (Amy Winehouse song)|Rehab]]\"\n| [[Amy Winehouse]]\n| 8\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 8\n| [[Music of the Philippines|OPM songs]]\n| \"[[Ang Huling El Bimbo]]\"\n| [[Eraserheads]]\n| 7\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 7\n| Songs from the [[1980s in music|1980s]]\n| \"[[Eternal Flame (song)|Eternal Flame]]\"\n| [[The Bangles]]\n| 3\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 6\n| Eraserheads or [[Rivermaya]]\n| \"[[Trip (Rivermaya album)|Kisapmata]]\"\n| Rivermaya\n| 4\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 5\n| Revival songs\n| \"[[Make You Feel My Love]]\"\n| [[Bob Dylan]]\n| 3\n| Safe\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Top 4\n| Songs from musical heroes\n| \"[[Forever (Chris Brown song)|Forever]]\"\n| [[Chris Brown (American entertainer)|Chris Brown]]\n| 3\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Bottom 2{{efn| 1 = Tandingan was in the bottom two but was saved by the judges' votes.}}\n|-\n| Final showdown\n| \"[[Ordinary People]]\"\n| [[John Legend]]\n| 2\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" | Finale\n| Contestant's choice\n| \"[[Superstar (Delaney and Bonnie song)|Superstar]]\"\n| [[The Carpenters]]\n| 3\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Winner\n|-\n| Celebrity duet\n| <small>Duet</small> \"[[The Way We Were (song)|The Way We Were]]\" <br/><small>with [[Rico J. Puno]]</small>\n| [[Barbra Streisand]]\n| 5\n|-\n| Mentor duet\n| {{nowrap|<small>Duet</small> \"[[The Way You Look Tonight]]\"<br/><small>with [[Charice Pempengco|Charice]]</small>}}\n| [[Fred Astaire]]\n| 1\n|}\n{{notelist| close}}\n\n===2012\u2013present: post ''The X Factor''===\nOn January 7, 2013, Tandingan entered the ''[[Himig Handog]]'' contest with the song entry called \"Scared To Death\", written by Domingo Rosco Jr. The song was accompanied with a music video that was assigned as a project to be directed by [[University of Santo Tomas]] and premiered on the 2nd of February in [[Myx|Myx Philippines]]. She performed the song in the grand finals on February 24, 2013 at the [[SM Mall of Asia Arena]]. Overall, the song finished in 4th place and was the third runner-up for Best P-pop Love Song thus rewarding the writer of Tandingan's song one hundred thousand pesos in cash.<ref name=\"Himig INQ\">{{cite news | url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/82603/director-composer-wins-himig-handog | title=Director-composer wins Himig Handog | newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | date=February 25, 2013 | accessdate=June 28, 2013 | author=Allan Policarpio}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://myxph.com/features/4934/anong-nangyari-sa-ating-dalawa-is-himig-handogs-best-p-pop-love-song/ | title=\"Anong Nangyari Sa Ating Dalawa\" Is HIMIG HANDOG's Best P-Pop Love Song! | publisher=[[Myx]] | accessdate=June 28, 2013 | author=Feliz Borja}}</ref> On April 21, 2013, she toured across North America as a supporting act for pop band [[Side A (band)|Side A]].<ref name=\"Himig INQ\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fatmediatv.com/#!side-a/cx2q | title=Side A 2013 | publisher=Fat Media TV | work=April 24, 2013 | accessdate=May 8, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421022948/http://www.fatmediatv.com/#!side-a/cx2q | archive-date=April 21, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> On May 2, 2013, Tandingan released her self-titled debut album. The album was produced by Jonathan Manalo and consists of mainly original songs with some covers.<ref name=\"debut\">{{cite web|title=KZ Tandingan Debut Album Snippets|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CeJFiXNcLgU|work=2 May 2013|publisher=Star Records|accessdate=3 May 2013}}</ref> On June 27, 2013, she officially launched the album on Makati City.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/06/28/13/kz-holds-successful-album-launch | title=KZ holds successful album launch | publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] | accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/98559/debut-album-shows-off-kz-tandingans-x-factor | title=Debut album shows off KZ Tandingan\u2019s \u2018X Factor\u2019 | newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | date=June 14, 2013 | accessdate=June 28, 2013 | author=Rito P. Asilo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.philstar.com/psn-showbiz/2013/06/05/950226/kz-tandingan-gustong-makapagbago-ng-buhay-sa-kanyang-mga-kanta | title=KZ Tandingan gustong makapagbago ng buhay sa kanyang mga kanta | newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]] | date=June 5, 2013 | accessdate=June 28, 2013 | language=Tagalog}}</ref>\n\nOn January 11, 2014, Tandingan won \u20b11,000,000 in ''[[The Singing Bee (Philippine game show)|The Singing Bee]]'' where she accumulated 4 straight songs correctly. In the show, she did not make a single error in the first 2 rounds and eventually won a tie-breaker against co-contestants Frenchie Dy and [[Sitti]], who also did not commit any errors throughout the game. The following year, she was announced as one of the eight contestants for the second season of ''[[Your Face Sounds Familiar (Philippines season 2)|Your Face Sounds Familiar]]'' along with [[Myrtle Sarrosa]], [[Sam Concepcion]], [[Cacai Bautista]], [[Kean Cipriano]], [[Denise Laurel]], [[Harana (band)|Michael Pangilinan]] and Eric Nicolas. The show ran from September 12, 2015 to December 13, 2015. and she was the 3rd runner-up. Tandingan was then announced as one of the celebrity mentors in ''[[We Love OPM]]'' in 2016, being the mentor of Team O Diva. The show ran from May 14, 2016 to July 17, 2016. She is currently seen in ''[[ASAP (variety show)|ASAP]]'', as one of the ASAP Soul Sessions with [[Jason Dy]], [[Daryl Ong]], [[Jay R]] and [[Kyla]]. The Soul Sessions formed on May 15, 2016, and disbanded in late 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/video/entertainment/08/13/17/kyla-jason-daryl-jay-r-kz-sing-bieber-hits-on-asap |title=Kyla, Jason, Daryl, Jay-R, KZ sing Bieber hits on 'ASAP' |date=August 13, 2017 |website=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====''[[Singer 2018]]''====\nOn February 9, 2018, Tandingan competed as a weekly challenger on [[China]]'s ''[[Singer 2018]]'' wherein she placed first on her debut round on week five. She sang her own rendition of [[Adele]]'s \"[[Rolling in the Deep]]\". She remained as a contestant on the show until her elimination on week nine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/02/09/18/kz-tandingan-beats-jessie-j-in-china-contest |title=KZ Tandingan beats Jessie J in China contest |date=February 9, 2018 |website=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 16, 2018, Tandingan sang the [[Mandopop]] song in her own rendition, \"The Hurts You Never Knew\" (Chinese: \u4f60\u4e0d\u77e5\u9053\u7684\u75db), a combination of three pieces of songs \"What Else Do You Want From Me\"(Chinese:\u4f60\u9084\u8981\u6211\u600e\u6a23) by [[Joker Xue]], \"All The Things You Never Knew\" (Chinese:\u4f60\u4e0d\u77e5\u9053\u7684\u4e8b) by [[Wang Leehom]] and \"Still Aching\" (Chinese:\u9084\u96b1\u96b1\u4f5c\u75db) by [[Power Station (Taiwanese band)|Power Station]]. She was allowed to remain in the competition for ranking third in the top four, per the competition rules for a challenger.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/02/19/18/kaya-pala-nag-iyakan-what-kzs-mandarin-song-means |title='Kaya pala nag-iyakan': What KZ's Mandarin song means |date=February 19, 2018 |website=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2018, Tandingan sang \"[[Royals (song)|Royals]]\" where she was the third person to perform. That week was a double elimination (after one contestant was too ill to perform and was given [[Bye (sports)|bye]] that week), and per the competition rules the two singers receiving the lowest count of overall votes would be eliminated. She finished last on the overall votes, resulted in her elimination of ''Singer 2018'' (another contestant, James Li, was also eliminated for finishing 7th on the overall count after a challenger of the week successfully placed in the top four).\n\nTandingan's stint in the show had made international music fans noticed her unique and creative musical artistry in different music genre. Her eventual elimination created a flurry of criticism from social media commentators and the Chinese fans she has built during her short stint in the show. On [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]], China's equivalent of [[Twitter]], KZ Tandingan became the second most talked about topic after her elimination.\n\nAs a rule, however, all eliminated singers except singers who withdrew and singer in the first round, returned for the breakout episode (aired April 6, 2018) for a chance to re-enter ''Singer 2018'' and qualify for the grand finals. Tandingan performed a Tagalog/Mandarin rendition of ''[[Anak (song)|Anak]]'' and finished 7th, and was unable to advance to the finals. Despite her elimination, she later returned as a guest singer (along with former winner [[Coco Lee]]) for a performance from [[Jessie J]] (who was the series winner) in the grand finals aired April 13, 2018.\n\n====DIVAS====\nOn April 27, 2016, Tandingan was announced to be part of the DIVAS girl group along with [[Kyla]], [[Yeng Constantino]], and [[Angeline Quinto]] ([[Rachelle Ann Go]] was originally planned to be part of the group, but left due to international commitments). The group staged their first concert titled DIVAS Live in Manila on [[November 11]], [[2016 in Philippine music|2016]] at the [[Smart Araneta Coliseum]]. On December 15, 2018, the group staged their second major concert at the Smart Araneta Coliseum with [[Boyz II Men]] titled Boyz II Men with DIVAS.\n\n==Discography==\n* ''[[KZ Tandingan (album)|KZ Tandingan]]'' (2013)\n* ''Soul Supremacy'' (2017)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Network\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2012\n| ''[[The X Factor Philippines (season 1)|The X Factor Philippines]]''\n| rowspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[ABS-CBN]]\n| Contestant\n| Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2012\u2013present\n| ''[[ASAP (variety show)|ASAP]]''\n| Herself\n| Main cast\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2013\u201316\n| ''[[Himig Handog]]''\n| Contestant\n| \"Scared To Death\" <small>(4th place)</small><br>\"Mahal Ko O Mahal Ako\" <small>(winner)</small><br>\"Laban Pa\" <small>(3rd place)</small>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2014\n| ''[[The Singing Bee (Philippine game show)|The Singing Bee]]''\n| Contestant\n| Winner; won \u20b11,000,000\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2015\n| ''[[Your Face Sounds Familiar (Philippines season 2)|Your Face Sounds Familiar]]''\n| Contestant\n| 4th place\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2016\n| ''[[We Love OPM]]''\n| Mentor    