 2013 | accessdate=June 28, 2013 | author=NR Ramos | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130624202604/http://mb.com.ph/Entertainment/Entertainment_Main/15485/Gloc-9_commands_26th_Awit_noms#.Uc2mGfk3DX4 | archivedate=June 24, 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"6\" | 2014\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[27th Awit Awards]]<br><small>by the ''[[Philippine Association of the Record Industry]]''</small>\n| \"Bakit Lumuluha\"<br><small>as ''Best Performance by a Female Recording Artist''</small>\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/12/13/14/gloc-9-nabs-top-honors-2014-awit-awards |title=Gloc 9 nabs top honors at 2014 Awit Awards |date=December 13, 2014 |website=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"Scared to Death\"<br><small>as ''Best Ballad Recording''</small>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| \"Darating Din\"<br><small>as ''Best Inspirational/Religious Recording''</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"Darating Din\"<br><small>as ''Best Jazz Recording''</small>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Myx Music Awards 2014]]<br><small>by ''[[Myx|MYX]]''</small>\n| KZ Tandingan<br><small>as ''Favorite Female Artist''</small>\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|last=Blanco|first=Eunice|title=Gloc9, Yeng, Sarah, Parokya ni Edgar win big at MYX Music Awards 2014|url=http://www.philstar.com/music/2014/03/27/1305706/gloc9-yeng-sarah-parokya-ni-edgar-win-big-myx-music-awards-2014|work=March 27, 2014|publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref> \n|-\n| KZ Tandingan<br><small>as ''Favorite New Artist''</small>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | 2015\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 28th Awit Awards<br><small>by the ''[[Philippine Association of the Record Industry]]''</small>\n| \"May Bukas Pa\" <small>(with Yeng Constantino)</small><br><small>as ''Best Collaboration''</small>\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.awitawards.com.ph/winners25th.html |title=WINNERS: 28th Awit Awards |date=December 9, 2015 |website=[[Philippine Association of the Record Industry]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"Mahal Ko O Mahal Ako\"<br><small>as ''Best Ballad Recording''</small>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! 2016\n| 29th Awit Awards<br><small>by the ''[[Philippine Association of the Record Industry]]''</small>\n| \"Wag Ka Nang Umiyak\" <small>(with Ebe Dancel)</small> <br><small>as ''Best Collaboration''</small>\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.awitawards.com.ph/29thAwitFinalists.pdf |title=List of 29th Awit Awards FINALISTS |website=[[Philippine Association of the Record Industry]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/12/08/16/sarah-g-ebe-dancel-win-big-at-29th-awit-awards |title=Sarah G, Ebe Dancel win big at 29th Awit Awards |date=December 8, 2016 |website=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" | 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 30th Awit Awards<br><small>by the ''[[Philippine Association of the Record Industry]]''</small>\n| \"Industriya\" <small>(with Gloc-9)</small> <br><small>as ''Best Collaboration''</small>\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/08/18/17/full-list-nominees-for-awit-awards-2017 |title=FULL LIST: Nominees for Awit Awards 2017 |date=August 18, 2017 |website=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pop.inquirer.net/2017/11/darren-espanto-inigo-pascual-win-big-30th-awit-awards/ |title=Darren Espanto, Inigo Pascual win big at 30th Awit Awards |date=November 29, 2017 |website=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"Industriya\" <small>(with Gloc-9)</small> <br><small>as ''Best Rap/HipHop Recording''</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2nd Wish 107.5 Music Awards <br><small>by ''[[DWNU|Wish 107.5 FM]]''</small>\n| \"Throwback\" <small>(as featured artist; with [[Morissette Amon]])</small><br><small>as ''Wish Original Song Of the Year by a Female Artist''</small>\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://bandera.inquirer.net/142367/morisette-hakot-queen-sa-2nd-wish-107-5-music-awards-jason-dy-darren-big-winner-din |title=Morisette \u2018Hakot Queen\u2019 sa 2nd Wish 107.5 Music Awards; Jason Dy, Darren big winner din |last=Santiago |first=Ervin |date=January 20, 2017 |website=[[Inquirer Bandera|Bandera]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"5\" | 2018\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 3rd Wish 107.5 Music Awards <br><small>by ''[[DWNU|Wish 107.5 FM]]''</small>\n| KZ Tandingan<br><small>as ''Wish Artist of the Year''</small>\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onemusic.ph/news/wish-107-5-announces-wish-music-awards-2018-3611 |title=Wish 107.5 announces Wish Music Awards 2018; List of nominees out now |last=Ortega |first=Karlos |date=December 19, 2017 |website=[[One Music]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.onemusic.ph/news/the-list-of-winners-from-wish-107-5-music-awards-3656 |title=The list of winners from Wish 107.5 Music Awards |last=Ortega |first=Karlos |date=January 15, 2018 |website=[[One Music]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"Two Less Lonely People in the World\"<br><small>as ''Wishclusive Pop Performance of the Year''</small>\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| \"Ikaw At Ako Pa Rin\" <small>(with TJ Monterde)</small><br><small>as ''Wishclusive Collaboration of the Year''</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"Labo\" by KZ Tandingan<br><small>as ''Wish Urban Song of the Year''</small>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| \"Win The Moment\" <small>(as featured artist; with Quest)</small><br><small>as ''Wish Urban Song of the Year''</small>\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{The X Factor Philippines |state=collapsed}}\n{{I Love OPM}}\n{{I Am a Singer}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tandingan, K. Z.}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Filipino female pop singers]]\n[[Category:Mandarin-language singers]]\n[[Category:The X Factor Philippines]]\n[[Category:The X Factor winners]]\n[[Category:Star Magic]]\n[[Category:Singers from Davao del Sur]]\n[[Category:Star Music artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Filipino singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Filipino singer and rapper}}\n{{About|the singer|her self-titled album|KZ Tandingan (album)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Philippine name|Lobrigas|Tandingan}}{{Infobox musical artist <!--Wikipedia:Musician -->\n| name             = KZ Tandingan\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = KZ Tandingan - 2019 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Tandingan in 2019\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = Kristine Zhenie Lobrigas Tandingan\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1992|03|11}}\n| birth_place      = [[Digos]], Philippines\n| origin           = Manila, Philippines\n| genre            = [[Acoustic music|Acoustic jazz]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| occupation       = Singer, rapper\n| instrument       = Vocals, piano\n| years_active     = 2012\u2013present\n| nationality      = [[Filipino people|Filipino]]\n| label            = [[Star Music]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Charice Pempengco]], [[List of The X Factor Philippines (season 1) finalists|''Factor'' finalists]], [[Side A (band)|Side A]], TJ Monterde, DIVAS, ASAP Soul Sessions\n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Kristine Zhenie Lobrigas Tandingan'''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ph.omg.yahoo.com/news/kz-wins--the-x-factor-philippines-.html | title=KZ wins 'The X Factor Philippines' | publisher=[[omg!|Yahoo! OMG! Philippines]]| date=October 8, 2012 | accessdate=June 28, 2013 | author=Karen Valeza}}</ref> (born March 11, 1992), mononymously known as '''KZ''', is a Filipino singer and rapper. She rose to prominence following her win on the [[The X Factor Philippines (season 1)|first season]] of ''[[The X Factor Philippines]]'' in 2012.<ref name=\"Champion X Factor\">{{cite web | url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/10/07/12/kz-tandingan-wins-x-factor-ph | title=KZ Tandingan wins 'X Factor PH' | publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] | date=October 7, 2012 | accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThat same year, she won [[Aliw Award|Aliw Award for Best New Artist]]. She has released notable songs in the Philippines such as \"Darating Din\", \"Mahal Ko o Mahal Ako\" and \"[[Two Less Lonely People in the World]]\", which peaked at number 2 on the [[Philippine Hot 100]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://billboard.ph/billboardph-hot-100-august-21/|title=billboard.ph - Diese Website steht zum Verkauf! - Informationen zum Thema .|website=billboard.ph|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref>\n\nTandingan is one of the members of the Filipino girl group DIVAS along with [[Yeng Constantino]], [[Kyla]], and [[Angeline Quinto]].\n\nShe became known internationally when she joined ''[[Singer 2018]]'', a popular singing competition aired on [[Hunan Broadcasting System|HBS]].\n\n==Life and career==\n===Early life===\nKZ Tandingan started singing as a child but had to stop when she was in her junior year in high school after suffering from a throat problem. She is an alumna of [[University of Southeastern Philippines]] in Davao City and had graduated with a degree of Bachelor of Science in Biology.<ref name=\"Philstar Bio\">{{cite news | url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2013/07/05/961692/will-kz-tandingan-make-it-stardom | title=Will KZ Tandingan make it to stardom? | newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]] | date=July 5, 2013 | accessdate=July 11, 2013 | author=Baby A. Gil}}</ref>\n\nBefore she joined ''The X Factor Philippines'', Tandingan was part of a local acoustic band.<ref name=\"Philstar Bio\"/>\n\n===2012: ''The X Factor Philippines''===\nTandingan was considered as an early favorite after she performed a jazzy version of \"[[Somewhere Over the Rainbow]]\" in the fourth week of the Judges' auditions. After receiving a standing ovation from all the judges', she was requested to sing again. Tandingan obliged and sang \"[[Ready or Not (Fugees song)|Ready or Not]]\" by American hip-hop group, [[The Fugees]]. With her second song, she also showed her rapping skills. Tandingan was greatly praised by all of the judges. Nievera even shouted that, \"A star is born in Digos!\".<ref name=\"ABS1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/07/16/12/star-born-digos-x-factor-week-3 | title='A star is born' in Digos on 'X Factor ' week 3 | publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Public Affairs|ABS-CBN News]] | date=July 16, 2012 | accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref> The video of Tandingan's audition went viral online after it was uploaded in YouTube. The video reached nearly 1 million views before it was removed due to copyright issues.<ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mindanaotimes.net/kz-enters-x-factor-top-20/ | title=KZ enters \u2018X Factor\u2019 Top 20 | publisher=[[Mindanao Times]] | date=July 24, 2012 | accessdate=July 31, 2012 | author=Fabian, Chris}}</ref> During the Bootcamp stage, she sang \"Mahirap Magmahal ng Syota ng Iba\" by the [[APO Hiking Society]] and cried after she made the cut for the Top 20.<ref name=\"ABS2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/07/23/12/kz-tandingan-x-factor-top-20-osang-out | title=KZ Tandingan in 'X Factor' Top 20; Osang out | publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Public Affairs|ABS-CBN News]] | date=July 23, 2012 | accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref> Tandingan sang \"[[Killing Me Softly with His Song]]\" by [[Roberta Flack]] during the Judges' home visit. On week 9, she landed on the bottom 2 for the first time with teammate Allen Sta. Maria, but she survived elimination. Tandingan was Charice's last remaining act after Allen Sta. Maria was eliminated on week 9. She reached the grand finals on October 7, 2012 and was proclaimed the winner of ''The X Factor Philippines''.<ref name=\"Champion X Factor\"/>\n\n;Performances and results\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible autocollapse\" style=\" margin:1em auto 1em auto; text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#BFBFBF;\"| ''The X Factor Philippines'' season 1 performances and results\n|-\n! Stage\n! Theme\n! Song choice\n! Original artist\n! Order \n! Result\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Audition\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Free choice\n| \"[[Over the Rainbow]]\"\n| [[Judy Garland]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Advanced\n|-\n| \"[[Ready or Not (Fugees song)|Ready or Not]]\"\n| [[Fugees]]\n|-\n! Bootcamp 1\n| Specific song\n| \"[[Without You (David Guetta song)|Without You]]\"\n| [[David Guetta]]\n| {{N/A}}\n| Advanced\n|-\n! Bootcamp 2\n| Free choice\n| \"[[APO Hiking Society#Songs|Mahirap Magmahal Ng Syota Ng Iba]]\"\n| {{nowrap|[[APO Hiking Society]]}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| Advanced\n|-\n! {{nowrap|Judges' houses}}\n| Free choice\n| \"[[Killing Me Softly with His Song]]\"\n| [[Roberta Flack]]\n| {{N/A}}\n| Advanced\n|-\n! Top 12\n| [[Soundtrack|Songs from the movies]]\n| \"[[The Show (Lenka song)|The Show]]\"\n| [[Lenka]]\n| 6\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 11\n| {{nowrap|song with [[Life]] or [[Life|Buhay]] in the title}}\n| \"[[For Once in My Life]]\"\n| [[Stevie Wonder]]\n| 9\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 10\n| [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| \"[[In the End]]\"\n| [[Linkin Park]]\n| 10\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 9\n| Tribute to late music icons\n| \"[[Rehab (Amy Winehouse song)|Rehab]]\"\n| [[Amy Winehouse]]\n| 8\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 8\n| [[Music of the Philippines|OPM songs]]\n| \"[[Ang Huling El Bimbo]]\"\n| [[Eraserheads]]\n| 7\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 7\n| Songs from the [[1980s in music|1980s]]\n| \"[[Eternal Flame (song)|Eternal Flame]]\"\n| [[The Bangles]]\n| 3\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 6\n| Eraserheads or [[Rivermaya]]\n| \"[[Trip (Rivermaya album)|Kisapmata]]\"\n| Rivermaya\n| 4\n| Safe\n|-\n! Top 5\n| Revival songs\n| \"[[Make You Feel My Love]]\"\n| [[Bob Dylan]]\n| 3\n| Safe\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Top 4\n| Songs from musical heroes\n| \"[[Forever (Chris Brown song)|Forever]]\"\n| [[Chris Brown (American entertainer)|Chris Brown]]\n| 3\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Bottom 2{{efn| 1 = Tandingan was in the bottom two but was saved by the judges' votes.}}\n|-\n| Final showdown\n| \"[[Ordinary People]]\"\n| [[John Legend]]\n| 2\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" | Finale\n| Contestant's choice\n| \"[[Superstar (Delaney and Bonnie song)|Superstar]]\"\n| [[The Carpenters]]\n| 3\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Winner\n|-\n| Celebrity duet\n| <small>Duet</small> \"[[The Way We Were (song)|The Way We Were]]\" <br/><small>with [[Rico J. Puno]]</small>\n| [[Barbra Streisand]]\n| 5\n|-\n| Mentor duet\n| {{nowrap|<small>Duet</small> \"[[The Way You Look Tonight]]\"<br/><small>with [[Charice Pempengco|Charice]]</small>}}\n| [[Fred Astaire]]\n| 1\n|}\n{{notelist| close}}\n\n===2012\u2013present: post ''The X Factor''===\nOn January 7, 2013, Tandingan entered the ''[[Himig Handog]]'' contest with the song entry called \"Scared To Death\", written by Domingo Rosco Jr. The song was accompanied with a music video that was assigned as a project to be directed by [[University of Santo Tomas]] and premiered on the 2nd of February in [[Myx|Myx Philippines]]. She performed the song in the grand finals on February 24, 2013 at the [[SM Mall of Asia Arena]]. Overall, the song finished in 4th place and was the third runner-up for Best P-pop Love Song thus rewarding the writer of Tandingan's song one hundred thousand pesos in cash.<ref name=\"Himig INQ\">{{cite news | url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/82603/director-composer-wins-himig-handog | title=Director-composer wins Himig Handog | newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | date=February 25, 2013 | accessdate=June 28, 2013 | author=Allan Policarpio}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://myxph.com/features/4934/anong-nangyari-sa-ating-dalawa-is-himig-handogs-best-p-pop-love-song/ | title=\"Anong Nangyari Sa Ating Dalawa\" Is HIMIG HANDOG's Best P-Pop Love Song! | publisher=[[Myx]] | accessdate=June 28, 2013 | author=Feliz Borja}}</ref> On April 21, 2013, she toured across North America as a supporting act for pop band [[Side A (band)|Side A]].<ref name=\"Himig INQ\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fatmediatv.com/#!side-a/cx2q | title=Side A 2013 | publisher=Fat Media TV | work=April 24, 2013 | accessdate=May 8, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421022948/http://www.fatmediatv.com/#!side-a/cx2q | archive-date=April 21, 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref> On May 2, 2013, Tandingan released her self-titled debut album. The album was produced by Jonathan Manalo and consists of mainly original songs with some covers.<ref name=\"debut\">{{cite web|title=KZ Tandingan Debut Album Snippets|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CeJFiXNcLgU|work=2 May 2013|publisher=Star Records|accessdate=3 May 2013}}</ref> On June 27, 2013, she officially launched the album on Makati City.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/06/28/13/kz-holds-successful-album-launch | title=KZ holds successful album launch | publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] | accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/98559/debut-album-shows-off-kz-tandingans-x-factor | title=Debut album shows off KZ Tandingan\u2019s \u2018X Factor\u2019 | newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | date=June 14, 2013 | accessdate=June 28, 2013 | author=Rito P. Asilo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.philstar.com/psn-showbiz/2013/06/05/950226/kz-tandingan-gustong-makapagbago-ng-buhay-sa-kanyang-mga-kanta | title=KZ Tandingan gustong makapagbago ng buhay sa kanyang mga kanta | newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]] | date=June 5, 2013 | accessdate=June 28, 2013 | language=Tagalog}}</ref>\n\nOn January 11, 2014, Tandingan won \u20b11,000,000 in ''[[The Singing Bee (Philippine game show)|The Singing Bee]]'' where she accumulated 4 straight songs correctly. In the show, she did not make a single error in the first 2 rounds and eventually won a tie-breaker against co-contestants Frenchie Dy and [[Sitti]], who also did not commit any errors throughout the game. The following year, she was announced as one of the eight contestants for the second season of ''[[Your Face Sounds Familiar (Philippines season 2)|Your Face Sounds Familiar]]'' along with [[Myrtle Sarrosa]], [[Sam Concepcion]], [[Cacai Bautista]], [[Kean Cipriano]], [[Denise Laurel]], [[Harana (band)|Michael Pangilinan]] and Eric Nicolas. The show ran from September 12, 2015 to December 13, 2015. and she was the 3rd runner-up. Tandingan was then announced as one of the celebrity mentors in ''[[We Love OPM]]'' in 2016, being the mentor of Team O Diva. The show ran from May 14, 2016 to July 17, 2016. She is currently seen in ''[[ASAP (variety show)|ASAP]]'', as one of the ASAP Soul Sessions with [[Jason Dy]], [[Daryl Ong]], [[Jay R]] and [[Kyla]]. The Soul Sessions formed on May 15, 2016, and disbanded in late 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/video/entertainment/08/13/17/kyla-jason-daryl-jay-r-kz-sing-bieber-hits-on-asap |title=Kyla, Jason, Daryl, Jay-R, KZ sing Bieber hits on 'ASAP' |date=August 13, 2017 |website=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====''[[Singer 2018]]''====\nOn February 9, 2018, Tandingan competed as a weekly challenger on [[China]]'s ''[[Singer 2018]]'' wherein she placed first on her debut round on week five. She sang her own rendition of [[Adele]]'s \"[[Rolling in the Deep]]\". She remained as a contestant on the show until her elimination on week nine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/02/09/18/kz-tandingan-beats-jessie-j-in-china-contest |title=KZ Tandingan beats Jessie J in China contest |date=February 9, 2018 |website=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 16, 2018, Tandingan sang the [[Mandopop]] song in her own rendition, \"The Hurts You Never Knew\" (Chinese: \u4f60\u4e0d\u77e5\u9053\u7684\u75db), a combination of three pieces of songs \"What Else Do You Want From Me\"(Chinese:\u4f60\u9084\u8981\u6211\u600e\u6a23) by [[Joker Xue]], \"All The Things You Never Knew\" (Chinese:\u4f60\u4e0d\u77e5\u9053\u7684\u4e8b) by [[Wang Leehom]] and \"Still Aching\" (Chinese:\u9084\u96b1\u96b1\u4f5c\u75db) by [[Power Station (Taiwanese band)|Power Station]]. She was allowed to remain in the competition for ranking third in the top four, per the competition rules for a challenger.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/02/19/18/kaya-pala-nag-iyakan-what-kzs-mandarin-song-means |title='Kaya pala nag-iyakan': What KZ's Mandarin song means |date=February 19, 2018 |website=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2018, Tandingan sang \"[[Royals (song)|Royals]]\" where she was the third person to perform. That week was a double elimination (after one contestant was too ill to perform and was given [[Bye (sports)|bye]] that week), and per the competition rules the two singers receiving the lowest count of overall votes would be eliminated. She finished last on the overall votes, resulted in her elimination of ''Singer 2018'' (another contestant, James Li, was also eliminated for finishing 7th on the overall count after a challenger of the week successfully placed in the top four).\n\nTandingan's stint in the show had made international music fans noticed her unique and creative musical artistry in different music genre. Her eventual elimination created a flurry of criticism from social media commentators and the Chinese fans she has built during her short stint in the show. On [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]], China's equivalent of [[Twitter]], KZ Tandingan became the second most talked about topic after her elimination.\n\nAs a rule, however, all eliminated singers except singers who withdrew and singer in the first round, returned for the breakout episode (aired April 6, 2018) for a chance to re-enter ''Singer 2018'' and qualify for the grand finals. Tandingan performed a Tagalog/Mandarin rendition of ''[[Anak (song)|Anak]]'' and finished 7th, and was unable to advance to the finals. Despite her elimination, she later returned as a guest singer (along with former winner [[Coco Lee]]) for a performance from [[Jessie J]] (who was the series winner) in the grand finals aired April 13, 2018.\n\n====DIVAS====\nOn April 27, 2016, Tandingan was announced to be part of the DIVAS girl group along with [[Kyla]], [[Yeng Constantino]], and [[Angeline Quinto]] ([[Rachelle Ann Go]] was originally planned to be part of the group, but left due to international commitments). The group staged their first concert titled DIVAS Live in Manila on [[November 11]], [[2016 in Philippine music|2016]] at the [[Smart Araneta Coliseum]]. On December 15, 2018, the group staged their second major concert at the Smart Araneta Coliseum with [[Boyz II Men]] titled Boyz II Men with DIVAS.\n\n==Discography==\n* ''[[KZ Tandingan (album)|KZ Tandingan]]'' (2013)\n* ''Soul Supremacy'' (2017)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"margin-right: 0;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Network\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2012\n| ''[[The X Factor Philippines (season 1)|The X Factor Philippines]]''\n| rowspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[ABS-CBN]]\n| Contestant\n| Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2012\u2013present\n| ''[[ASAP (variety show)|ASAP]]''\n| Herself\n| Main cast\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2013\u201316\n| ''[[Himig Handog]]''\n| Contestant\n| \"Scared To Death\" <small>(4th place)</small><br>\"Mahal Ko O Ma